		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Kj DellâAntonia			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-03T22:19:49+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 3, 2014 5:19 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 3, 2014 5:19 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/03/writer-rejected-for-a-retail-job-is-embraced-and-vilified-on-facebook/" data-title="Writer, Rejected for a Retail Job, Is Embraced and Vilified on Facebook" data-description="A story of a failed marriage and financial implosion provokes equal and opposite reactions on Facebook. Why? ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/03/us/motherlode-copaken/motherlode-copaken-blog480.png" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/03/us/motherlode-copaken/motherlode-copaken-blog480.png" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/03/us/motherlode-copaken/motherlode-copaken-blog480.png" id="100000003213182" width="480" height="391" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="391"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was the usual Sunday night Facebook scroll. To be honest, what really caught my eye on Deborah Copaken&#8217;s &#8220;<a href="//www.cafe.com/r/15cfcec0-e537-4231-bd74-58f223ab0c9d/1/the-illusion-of-control-or-how-i-got-rejected-from-a-job-at-the-container-store">How I Got Rejected From a Job at The Container Store</a>&#8221; was the image, which was of containers. I like containers; clearly, many of us do, thus The Container Store.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recognized Ms. Copaken&#8217;s name, though (from &#8220;Shutterbabe&#8221; and &#8220;Hell Is Other Parents&#8221;). Clicked, read. And, in spite of copious use of the &#8220;Reader&#8221; trope (as in, &#8220;Reader, I married him&#8221;) and the word &#8220;Harvard&#8221; (after a certain age, I think we probably need to stop defining ourselves by our undergraduate histories), I saw myself, and many women I know, in her essay. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;s easy to imagine the few chunks of bad luck combined with poor judgment that could land many of us in her shoes, without health insurance, without an income and rejected from a seasonal retail job. I shared it, and because you have to write something, called it a Halloween horror story that could happen to any of us. This was not deep reasoning. It was Facebook reasoning: fast, dirty and click-click-click.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My gut reaction â there, but for a whole bunch of things, some of which I control, some which I don&#8217;t, go I â was one I saw echoed in many shares of this essay on Facebook. But there was another reaction, about equally prevalent in my feed: Many readers called Ms. Copaken entitled, whiny, and worse, as she wrote: </p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because seriously, if an Emmy-award-winning, New York Times bestselling author and Harvard grad cannot land a job as a greeter at The Container Store â or anywhere else for that matter, hard as I tried â we are all doomed.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Rereading more critically, I could see that perspective as well. I had noted, even the first time through, that if you really want a job at The Container Store, you do not fill out an online form. You go to The Container Store. You smile. You schmooze. You beg, and you reappear regularly, applying the kind of single-minded dedication to your quest that, you assure them, you will to your job. You do not brandish a rÃ©sumÃ© strikingly different from that of other employees at The Container Store, either. You gloss over periods of glory in much the same way that others gloss over periods of unemployment. If Harvard does not teach its students that in some situations, a Harvard degree is not an advantage, then Harvard is doing its students a disservice. One might even think that Ms. Kopaken did not actually want a job at The Container Store, but rather, what she got: a rejection from The Container Store and a metaphor for her disorganized, chaotic present and her uncertain future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I wasn&#8217;t so much moved by The Container Store&#8217;s rejection of Ms. Copaken as I was by the rest of her story: the layoff, the disappearing husband, the abrupt and confusing end to Cobra insurance coverage, the breast cancer diagnosis, the insurance application windows â the whole litany of possibly preventable-but-who-can-plan-for-everything bad luck. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But where I put more weight on the misfortune, others saw bad judgment, a lack of savings and a sense of entitlement â and in some cases added that they suspected that her New York-apartment-dwelling, sold-a-television-pilot self might be feeling stretched, but couldn&#8217;t really feel the desperation she was laying claim to. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">From what I could see across my Facebook page, it wasn&#8217;t a split along gender lines (although it came close). It wasn&#8217;t a split along political lines (although, again, it came close â but not that close). We all read the same essay. But we pressed &#8220;share&#8221; or &#8220;comment&#8221; and said very, very different things. That&#8217;s often true, but this time it really intrigued me. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How about you? When you read Ms. Copaken&#8217;s story, or even the little I&#8217;ve shared here, do you identify with her or dismiss her â and more interestingly, why? </p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	    </div>
</footer>
